pullRequest.title: Fix linkage errors, qualifier handling, NPE in metrics processing, and revert Xerces upgrade
pullRequest.bodyText:
What does this PR do?
Fixes a few bugs identified during testing on a downstream project. In particular:

Fixes a couple of linkage errors encountered when using SOAP endpoints
Fixes an assumption in code that a qualifier on a query always indicates a search for a derived resource. There is at least one known use case where this is not true.
Fixes an NPE in pre-query metrics processing
Reverts a Xerces upgrade as it was causing WSDL policy injection to fail for secure SOAP endpoints

Who is reviewing it?
@stustison @paouelle @blen-desta @bakejeyner @garrettfreibott
How should this be tested?

Any background context you want to provide?
What are the relevant tickets?
Fixes: #6168
Screenshots

Checklist:

 Documentation Updated
 Update / Add Threat Dragon models
 Update / Add Unit Tests
 Update / Add Integration Tests

Notes on Review Process
Please see Notes on Review Process for further guidance on requirements for merging and abbreviated reviews.
Review Comment Legend:

✏️ (Pencil) This comment is a nitpick or style suggestion, no action required for approval. This comment should provide a suggestion either as an in line code snippet or a gist.
❓ (Question Mark) This comment is to gain a clearer understanding of design or code choices, clarification is required but action may not be necessary for approval.
❗ (Exclamation Mark) This comment is critical and requires clarification or action before approval.

commit.message:
Fix linkage errors

Endorses ServiceMix saaj-api and activation-api bundles and exports
their packages from bundle 0. This fixes an issue in Karaf causing
linkage errors.
Change qualifier handling to respect use cases other than derived resources

Revert "DDF-6075 Dependency Upgrades [2.21.x] (#6098)"

This reverts commit cbb8be60c8223f814d84a4e48af3c4f50630ccca.
Check for empty collection to avoid NoSuchElementException from Iterator.next()

     // check if the resource request included a qualifier in which case we are trying to retrieve
     // a derived resource and not the resource
     final Serializable qualifier = resourceReq.getPropertyValue(ResourceRequest.QUALIFIER);
-
-    if (qualifier == null) { // no qualifier means we are retrieving the resource
+    final String scheme = resourceInfo.getResourceUri().getScheme();
+
+    // no qualifier means we are retrieving the resource
+    // presence of a qualifier can mean different things. We interpret it based on protocol:
+    //   - content: this always means we are retrieving a derived resource.
+    //   - http(s): we assume the intent is to retrieve a derived resource. Is this always true?
+    //   - other: we assume we are retrieving the resource. This assumption is based on experience
+    //            with protocols that use the qualifier for purposes other than derived resources.
+    //            If protocols besides content and http(s) need to support derived resources, this
+    //            could be an issue.
+    if (qualifier == null || !Arrays.asList("http", "https", "content").contains(scheme)) {
